Topic:8 Reporting File system disk space usage
----------------------------------------------
Learn how to check disk and memory usage easily on linux

Disk space usage commands:
	.df -h : Report file system disk space usage (human readable)
	.du -h : Estimate file space usage(human readable)
	
Memory Usage Commands:
	.free : Display amount of free and used memory in the system
	.free -h : Human readable memory output
	.free -k : Display memory in kilobytes(KB)
	.free -m : Display memory usage in megabytes(MB)
	.free -g : Display memory usage in gigabytes(GB)

Topic:9 Package management:
---------------------------
.is used to install, update, configure and remove software.
.It ensures that software package and dependencies are handled properly and maintain(secure and manage their system efficently)	
	 
Example:
	
	.Web server -> serves websites (e.g., Apache, Nginx)
	.Database server -> stores and manages data (e.g., MySQL, Postgres, microsoft etc)
	.File Server -> stores and shares files between servers
	.Mail server -> handles emails (e.g., Microsoft Exchange)
	.Application Server -> runs business logics
	
EC2 server:
-----------	
	when you choose amazon Linux/debian/ubuntu/redhat/centos:
	
	Task:					Debian/Ubuntu:					Redhat/Amazon linux/CentOS:
	--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	Update					sudo apt update					sudo yum update
	upgrade all packages	sudo apt upgrade				sudo yum upgrade
	Install package			sudo apt install packagename	sudo yum install packagename
	remove package			sudo apt remove packagename		sudo yum remove packagename
	List installed packages	apt list --installed			yum list installed
	
Key Features & Functions:

	.Install: add new software
	.Upgrade: update installed packages
	.Remove: Uninstall software



TOPIC:10 Service Management:
----------------------------
you can start, stop, restart and monitor service

Key service managment commands:
-------------------------------
For Example:
	
Action:					Command Example:
----------------------------------------
start service			sudo systemctl start service
stop service			sudo systemctl stop service
restart service			sudo systemctl restart service

Examples:
	.Start Apache: sudo systemctl start nginx/apache/httpd
	.stop Apache: sudo systemctl stop httpd
	.restart Apache: sudo systemctl restart httpd
